user_message:
An agent A claimed that the following MHD_get_timeout_i code violates the MISRA C 2023 rule 2.1.
<misra_rule>
MISRA C 2023 Rule 2.1 is A project shall not contain unreachable code.

</misra_rule>
<target_code>
Here is the original code of MHD_get_timeout_i.
```c
_MHD_EXTERN int
MHD_get_timeout_i (struct MHD_Daemon *daemon)
{
#if SIZEOF_INT >= SIZEOF_INT64_T
  return MHD_get_timeout64s (daemon);
#else  /* SIZEOF_INT < SIZEOF_INT64_T */
  const int64_t to64 = MHD_get_timeout64s (daemon);
  if (INT_MAX >= to64)
    return (int) to64;
  return INT_MAX;
#endif /* SIZEOF_INT < SIZEOF_INT64_T */
}
```
</target_code>
<response format>
Provide your answer with these fields.
- explanation: your evaluation of the scenario provided by the agent A.
- is_report_correct: whether the report is correct or not (true/false). True means there is a violation.
</response format>
<scenario>
The agent A provided the following violation scenario:
Given the project definitions SIZEOF_INT = 4 and SIZEOF_INT64_T = 8, the preprocessor condition #if SIZEOF_INT >= SIZEOF_INT64_T is always false. As a result the code in the #if branch (the first return MHD_get_timeout64s(daemon);) is never compiled or executed in the project configuration, i.e. it is unreachable/dead code.
</scenario>
<additional code>Here are the definitions of symbols that are close to the target function MHD_get_timeout_i:
#define SIZEOF_INT 4
